   Recherchesen Informatique Communicat},
Abstract = {We study the security of Cyber-Physical Systems (CPS) where sensors are
   subject to cyber-attacks. Specifically, we consider CPS control systems
   where sensor readings may be compromised by a malicious attacker intent
   on causing damage to the system. We study this problem at the
   supervisory layer of the control system, using discrete event systems
   techniques. We assume that the attacker can edit the outputs from the
   sensors of the system before they reach the supervisory controller.
   In the first step, we consider the problem from the viewpoint of the
   attacker, where the goal is to use edit attacks on the sensor readings
   to steer the system to an unsafe state without being detected. In the
   second step, we consider defense mechanisms and formulate the problem of
   synthesizing a supervisor that is robust against a large class of edit
   attacks.
