   Motors Co; MathWorks; Halliburton; dSPACE; Int Journal Automat Comp;
   Altair; Soc Ind Appl Math; Wiley; Quanser; Temple Univ; Journal Franklin
   Inst; IEEE CAA Journal Automatica Sinica; Processes},
Abstract = {We study the security of control systems in the context of the
   supervisory control layer of stochastic discrete-event systems. Control
   systems heavily rely on correct communication between the plant and the
   controller. In this work, we consider that such communication is
   partially compromised by a malicious attacker. The attacker has the
   ability to modify a subset of the sensor readings and mislead the
   supervisor, with the goal of inducing the system into an unsafe state.
   We consider this problem from the attacker's viewpoint and investigate
   the synthesis of an attack strategy for systems modeled as probabilistic
   automata. Specifically, we quantify each attack strategy based on the
