Month = {OCT},
Abstract = {This note investigates enforcement of opacity by nondeterministic edit
   functions. The edit functions alter the system's output by inserting
   fictitious events or erasing observed events. The edit decisions are
   randomly made while not known by the outside environment a priori. There
   is an intruder characterized as a passive observer with malicious goals
   to infer the secrets of the system. We require that opacity be enforced
   when the intruder may or may not know the implementation of edit
   functions. This requirement is termed as private and public safety. We
   also restrict the operation of edit functions by defining edit
   constraints. Then, the opacity enforcement problem is transformed to a
   three-player game among the edit function, the environment, and a dummy
   player, which helps to determine edit decisions. A game structure called
   the all edit structure (AES) is introduced to characterize the
   interaction among those players. It embeds all privately safe edit
   functions and may also embed publicly safe edit functions. Based on the
   AES, we present an algorithm that provably synthesizes nondeterministic
   edit functions that satisfy both private safety and public safety.},
