Year = {2022},
Volume = {6},
Pages = {890-895},
Abstract = {In this letter, we consider the problem of verifying initial-state
   opacity for networks of discrete-time control systems. We formulate the
   opacity property as a safety one over an appropriately constructed
   augmented system, and aim to verify this latter property by finding
   suitable barrier certificates. To reduce the computational complexity
   associated with computing barrier certificates for large networks, we
   propose a compositional approach to construct such barrier certificates
   for large-scale interconnected systems. This is achieved by introducing
   local barrier certificates for subsystems in the network and imposing
   some small-gain type conditions on the gains of those local barrier
   certificates. We also provide sufficient conditions for verifying the
   lack of opacity in large-scale networks by constructing barrier
   certificates ensuring some reachability properties over the augmented
   systems. To illustrate the effectiveness of our results, we consider the
   problem of tracking a target using a team of vehicles and verify if its
   initial position is secret from possible outside intruders.},
